																															<p style="font-size: 12px; margin-top: 0;"><img alt="Robotics in Research - Robotic needle-driver and ultrasound arms attached to a CT scanner test automatic needle placement for biopsy and tumor ablation with point-and-click accuracy" src="/sites/nihinternet/files/internet-files/researchers/_img/researchers_photo1.jpg" width="100%" /> <strong>Robotics in Research</strong> - Robotic needle-driver and ultrasound arms attached to a CT scanner test automatic needle placement for biopsy and tumor ablation with point-and-click accuracy.</p>

<p style="font-size: 12px;"><img alt="Fusion Imaging - 3D colorized-fusion imaging defines tumors as targets for thermal ablation" src="/sites/nihinternet/files/internet-files/researchers/_img/researchers_photo2.jpg" width="100%" /> <strong>Fusion Imaging</strong> - 3D colorized-fusion imaging defines tumors as targets for thermal ablation.</p>

<p style="font-size: 12px;"><img alt="Holographic Globe - 3D spatial visualization moves beyond regular display monitors to show inside the body during procedures. The colon is blue, the liver is red, and there is a hole in the liver where a tumor was cooked with needles in a minimally-invasive, image-guided procedure" src="/sites/nihinternet/files/internet-files/researchers/_img/researchers_photo3.jpg" width="100%" /> <strong>Holographic Globe</strong> - 3D spatial visualization moves beyond regular display monitors to show inside the body during procedures. The colon is blue, the liver is red, and there is a hole in the liver where a tumor was cooked with needles in a minimally-invasive, image-guided procedure.</p>

